Increase in request to participate in future research</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-7490945614.40026952b36c3b8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Metapragmatic awareness in children who have pragmatic language impairments: exploring the relationship to conversational behaviour</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>5D4C6090-CBE2-4276-B7C7-07865D6553A3</gtr:id><gtr:impact>In this presentation we outline new work being carried out at the University of Manchester UK, which aims to develop a new clinical assessment of metapragmatics in school age children. Metapragmatic awareness and the role of metalinguistic ability in communication will be defined as well as the literature on the growth of these skills in children with typical language development. Current research knowledge on clinical application of metapragmatic strategies in intervention will then be outlined. One notable gap in knowledge is how metapragmatics develops in the school years and how this could be assessed in a child-friendly manner. 

In the second part of the presentation we will describe the development of a novel Assessment of Metapragmatics (AMPs) which uses video scenarios to prompt reflective comments from the children. Preliminary results are presented. AMPs has been used within a related project, The Social Communication Intervention Project SCIP (UK): a randomised controlled trial of intervention for one type of social communication impairment. The potential of metapragmatic ability as a mediator of intervention will be discussed.

